Span.Text: Make sense of extensive and complicated data to act more quickly and effectively.

“Information can now be collected from a great many sources. For example, intelligent street lighting will help us to detect and record air quality, noise pollution and footfall all over the city. It’s not just the council or big business who will benefit. Anyone who has a vested interest will be able to understand the services people may need."
Colin Birchenhall, Lead Architect, Future City Glasgow

Microsoft dashboards provide a simplified view of performance and contextual data.  Information from multiple sources based on a multistage process such as a ‘planning application’ can be aggregated into a view that’s clearer, delivering more actionable insights.  Users are empowered with the self-service ability to define unique perspectives on business information, driving down IT resource operational overheads.

Uncover unexpected patterns and associations and develop models to guide front-line interactions. Evaluate trends and gauge constituent interaction with departments. Use data to create strategies that enhance service and at the same time reduce costs.
Create a data-driven security approach for mission-critical priorities.  Use insight from big data analysis to understand emerging threats and recover more quickly with improved response decisions.

Make data security enhanced and accessible to citizens and staff without any requirements for identification or registration, and for any purpose, possibly in an open format and not subject to any trademark or copyright concerns.
